<div class="two-col">
  <div class="key-box" style="background:#f0f8f0;border:2px solid var(--green)">
    <div class="key-title" style="color:var(--green)">Key 1 — Alkalinity<br/><small style="font-weight:normal;font-size:.8rem">Primary role: solubility</small></div>
    <div class="key-body">
      Alkalinity does two essential things:<br/><br/>
      <b>Stage 1 — Creates the bacterial environment.</b> Alkaliphilic bacteria thrive
      at pH 9–10. Without alkalinity they cannot function.<br/><br/>
      <b>Stage 3 — Ionizes the disrupted molecule.</b> After bacteria convert C=O to C-OH,
      alkalinity deprotonates the C-OH groups. The first deprotonation (pKa 8.0) gives the
      molecule a negative charge. That charge attracts water, and the molecule dissolves.

      Without this ionization, the reduced molecule stays at the bottom of the vat as a
      useless colorless solid.
    </div>

  </div>
  <div class="key-box" style="background:#f0f4ff;border:2px solid var(--ind)">
    <div class="key-title" style="color:var(--ind)">Key 2 — Bacteria<br/><small style="font-weight:normal;font-size:.8rem">Primary role: breaking the color</small></div>
    <div class="key-body">
      <b>Stage 2 — Reduce the conjugated system.</b> Specific alkaliphilic bacteria —
      <em>Alkalibacterium</em>, <em>Bacillus</em>, <em>Clostridium</em> — donate electrons
      into the molecule's conjugated π system through Extracellular Electron Transfer (EET).<br/><br/>
      Because the molecule is a single connected system (N, C=O, C=C, C=O, N), the electrons
      distribute across it: C=C becomes C–C (chromophore gone, color disappears), and C=O
      becomes C-OH (the hydrogen bond lattice is disrupted).<br/><br/>
      Without bacteria, alkalinity alone cannot break the C=C or disrupt the lattice.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<div style="background:var(--faint);border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:var(--radius);padding:.75rem 1rem;margin-top:.75rem;font-family:var(--ff-body);font-size:.88rem;color:var(--ink);line-height:1.7">
  <b>The sequence:</b> Alkalinity first — creates the bacterial environment and prepares
  for ionization → Bacteria reduce the C=C — color disappears, leuco form created →
  Alkalinity ionizes the leuco molecule — it dissolves in solution, ready to dye.
The two keys are mutually dependent: alkalinity enables bacteria, and bacteria
produce a molecule that alkalinity can dissolve. Neither works without the other.

</div>
